While this works fine with the current Galaxy UI, I'd like to get users logged in as transparently as possible without having to get first into the login page of Galaxy and then click the button. A simple solution for this could be instead of return a JSON, doing the actual redirect.

I have modified [`lib/galaxy/webapps/galaxy/controllers/authnz.py`](https://github.com/galaxyproject/galaxy/blob/113430fd457bfae4255f7b498f3dade5e2381563/lib/galaxy/webapps/galaxy/controllers/authnz.py#L75) in my local instance to do that, trying to minimise changes in any other parts of the code and keep things working anywhere else:

```
--- lib/galaxy/webapps/galaxy/controllers/authnz.py.orig        2024-03-20 08:58:33.775207554 +0000
+++ lib/galaxy/webapps/galaxy/controllers/authnz.py     2024-03-20 08:59:53.646016455 +0000
@@ -73,14 +73,17 @@

     @web.json
     @web.expose
-    def login(self, trans, provider, idphint=None):
+    def login(self, trans, provider, idphint=None, **kwargs):
         if not trans.app.config.enable_oidc:
             msg = "Login to Galaxy using third-party identities is not enabled on this Galaxy instance."
             log.debug(msg)
             return trans.show_error_message(msg)
         success, message, redirect_uri = trans.app.authnz_manager.authenticate(provider, trans, idphint=idphint)
         if success:
-            return {"redirect_uri": redirect_uri}
+            if kwargs.get("redirect", None) == "true":
+                return trans.response.send_redirect(redirect_uri)
+            else:
+                return {"redirect_uri": redirect_uri}
         else:
             raise exceptions.AuthenticationFailed(message)
```

This works and I can send a PR, but not sure if this the best approach or if there are existing PRs where this could be integrated.

